I can never understand why, in the US, there is such a fear of 'time off', such a constant emphasis on working and working.
tbh it‚Äôs like a bruteforce approach, but honestly the best work happens spontaneously and to ones‚Äô own schedule
In Europe, it's mandatory that there's at least a month of time set aside for holidays, usually in 2 week blocks or summat...though employers like to exploit loopholes sometimes..
It‚Äôs funny because it‚Äôs a double standard comparing higher up the chain and the more common workers
The same work groups too that used to allow more flexibility have whittled down over time too in favor of ‚Äòcost savings‚Äô
So like where there were pools of workers potentially on schedule, the size of that type of thing has shrunk over time
So, basically 'more money for me' again.
Cuz ultimately the ‚Äòcost cutters‚Äô get the gratitude and bonuses and such
That‚Äôs why the disappearnce of unions is a problem, really
What's actually behind the disappearence of Unions anyway, and d'you think they can make a comeback?
I feel like laws have more bent toward the side of employers‚Äô rights?
I just feel like unions in general have less teeth than they used to where they exist
Cuz the whole personal governance/negotiaton became the selling point of modern employment
Which works for a good amount of the workforce
It‚Äôs more free market rules vs regulation
Free market being the one-for-all-all-for-one leave-if-you-don‚Äôt-like-it mentality
...that might not work in the long run.
But it‚Äôs easier for big players (i.e. employers) to game a ‚Äòfree market‚Äô
No matter what we aspire to, some of us WILL need to do the dirtier work. Sanitation, Construction, all that
The things that people don't normally think about.
Individuals overall have very little influence over a market overall
If I could I'd just play games, read and draw all the time.
But I think that I could do a lot by becoming a surveyor.
Only TRENDS in labor can influenece a particular worker‚Äôs experienec
Yeah the free market works best for those with some sort of specialized skills
Surveyors are in a bit of a pickle...on the one hand, not enough for demand, on the other, Covid
Work placement is starting late 'cause of it.
I'm taking the extra time to break some bad habits and actually develop a work ethic.
Yeah, an economic slowdown brings less activity to ALL business
Everything is connected somehow, less money flowing in one part of the economy causes flow to slow everywhere
varying amounts of effect, but not the same as if things were ‚Äònormal‚Äô
There is never really a 'normal' though...is there?
